@@eShadowmere, the Blighted Crownlands@@N

Shadowmere is not merely a haunted fortress. It is the ruin of a
@@ystate project@@N: a frontier march founded to extend Midgaard's law,
logistics, and burial order into unstable territory. Its modern
horror comes from policy choices that outlived their emergency context.

In the generation after Midgaard's early road-security accords, the
Crown sponsored a fortified march-town at a crossroads of military
roads, farm belts, and burial tracts. Its mandate was practical:
guard transit, tax goods, process the war dead and plague dead before
they reached core districts, and keep records admissible in tribunals.

Then came the @@rPlague Mandate@@N. When blight-fevers spread, emergency
directives authorized rapid intake, forced quarantines, immediate
cremation powers, and suspension of lineage appeals. Temporary became
permanent. Shadowmere built trenches, processing halls, and deep
binding cells. What had been a frontier court became an @@rintake
machine@@N for the dead and near-dead.

After plague peaks receded, no authority agreed on rollback. Crown
envoys demanded noble precedence. Compact wardens insisted containment
powers remain. Temple delegates sought release rites for mass graves.
March commanders refused to relinquish emergency chains. The @@rLast
Bell Crisis@@N saw three contradictory decrees rung in one night:
amnesty, lockdown, and requisition. The city calcified into mutually
hostile systems.

The @@dBlight Hydrology Doctrine@@N tells the environmental story.
Original design routed runoff through burial and quarantine districts.
During crisis years, alchemical disposal and preservative salts
entered the same channels. Sealed crypts flooded from below. Low
fields became permanent toxic wetlands. The blight is not accidental
corruption -- it is @@rinfrastructure memory@@N.

Five factions invoke law but none can establish legitimacy. The
@@WOathbound March@@N -- undead soldiers executing obsolete orders. The
@@rCrimson Household@@N -- aristocratic predators claiming bloodline
continuity. The @@dBinder Collegium@@N -- necromancer-clerks treating
souls as ledger entries. The @@rGallows Syndicate@@N -- execution
specialists who turned sentence infrastructure into an economy. And
the @@eFen-Adapted Remnants@@N -- feral populations proving ecological
succession beyond governance.

Shadowmere is what happens when lawful systems become predatory under
emergency powers without sunset. Orders are stamped, witnessed,
sealed, and wrong.
